<theorem xml:id="th_infinite_limits">
    <title>Infinite limit formulas</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. We have 
            <md>
                <mrow>\lim_{x\to \infty}x^n \amp= \infty \amp \lim_{x\to -\infty}x^n\amp=\infty \amp (\text{ if } n \text{ even}) </mrow>
                <mrow>\lim_{x\to \infty}x^n \amp= \infty \amp \lim_{x\to -\infty}x^n\amp=-\infty \amp (\text{ if } n \text{ odd}) </mrow>
            </md>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Fix a constants <m>a,b\in \R</m>, where <m>b&gt; 0</m>. Let <m>f</m> be a function. 
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    If <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a^+}f(x)=0</m>, then 
                                    <me>
                                        \lim\limits_{x\to a^+}\frac{b}{f(x)}=\begin{cases}
                                        \infty \amp \text{if } f(x)&gt; 0 \text{ on open interval } (0,c) \\
                                        -\infty \amp \text{if } f(x)&lt; 0 \text{ on open interval } (0,c) 
                                        \end{cases}
                                    </me>
                                    
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    If <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a^-}f(x)=0</m>, then 
                                    <me>
                                        \lim\limits_{x\to a^-}\frac{1}{f(x)}=\begin{cases}
                                        \infty \amp \text{if } f(x)&gt; 0 \text{ on open interval } (c,0) \\
                                        -\infty \amp \text{if } f(x)&lt; 0 \text{ on open interval } (c,0) 
                                        \end{cases}
                                    </me>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</theorem>
<remark xml:id="rm_def_indef">
<title>Definite forms</title>
<p>
There is considerable more subtlety involved when trying to formulate limit laws that are applicable to infinite limits. Instead of burdening you with a long official theorem with many cases and subcases, we instead enumerate a few informal principles you can use when dealing with infinite limits. The bits arithmetic notation that accompany these principles are called <term>definite forms</term>. They are to be considered simply as shorthand for a careful observation about functions whose value approach <m>\infty</m>, <m>-\infty</m>, or <m>0</m>. You can cite these definite forms in your <em>parenthetical justifications</em> of steps in limit computations. See examples below for models of these computations. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            Definite form: 
            <md>
                <mrow>\infty+\infty \amp =\infty \amp -\infty-\infty=-\infty</mrow>
            </md>.
            Principle: large positive number <m>+</m> large positive number <m>=</m> large positive number. (Similarly for negative case.)
        </p>
    </li>
    <li><p>
        Definite form: 
        <md>
            <mrow>\infty\cdot \infty \amp =\infty \amp \infty\cdot(-\infty)=-\infty</mrow>
        </md>.
        Principle: large positive number <m>\times</m> large positive number <m>=</m> large positive number; large positive number <m>\times</m> large negative number <m>=</m> large negative number. 
    </p>
</li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Definite form: 
            <md>
                <mrow>\frac{\text{bounded}}{\pm \infty} \amp = 0</mrow>
            </md>.
            Principle: if numerator values are bounded in absolute value, and denominator values get arbitrarily large, then quotient approaches <m>0</m>. A common instance of this principle is encoded by the definite form 
            <me>
                \frac{c}{\pm \infty}=0
            </me>,
            where <m>c</m> is a constant. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Definite form:
            <md>
